LISTERIOSIS, RISK ASSESSMENT USING MOUSE MODEL (03)
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Listeriosis, risk assessment using mouse model 980306221111
Listeriosis, risk assessment using mouse model (02) 980308234443
Date: Mon, 09 Mar 1998 07:33:34 -0500
From: Robert A. LaBudde <ral@lcfltd.com>

I am a reasonably healthy male 50-yr. old, and came down with a mild case of
foodborne listeriosis last summer. The etiological agent was _L.
monocytogenes_ in a package of Orvall-Kent potato salad purchased at Super
K-Mart. The product was recalled for Listeria contamination by the company.
At the time, no cases of infection were reported.
The strain involved in my sickness was probably serotype 1/2b, since a
complex of symptoms occurred about 24 hr. after ingestion of the food. These
symptoms included fever, headache, body ache, slight nausea and malaise.
Within 24 hr. all symptoms disappeared.
The potato salad had been totally consumed and the container discarded. I
would never have associated the symptoms with listeriosis, except for
receiving
a notice of recall of the particular food item on one of the listserves I
subscribe to. Since the illness was minor and ephemeral, no stool cultures
were taken, so the agent was not conclusively identified.
All this means is that mild cases are rarely reported, but still occur.
--
